ention": "SR-B1 gene families", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9529383778572083, "span": {"begin": 676, "end": 695}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000728"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "androgen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9887704849243164, "span": {"begin": 733, "end": 741}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006058"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "malformation of reproductive organs", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999822378158569, "span": {"begin": 815, "end": 850}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013196"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "dihydrotesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999327540397644, "span": {"begin": 905, "end": 921}}, {"id": ["mesh:C032279"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "phthalates", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.998636782169342, "span": {"begin": 991, "end": 1001}}], "text": "In this key event relationship we are focused on the decrease in abundance of steroidogenesis enzymes involved in the synthesis of steroid compounds and corresponding decrease in dihydrotestosterone levels. &nbsp;Steroidogenesis is the process of generating hormones starting from cholesterol as precursor to create a variety of steroid structures via enzyme catalyzed reactions.&nbsp; A large number of genes are involved in regulating steroidogenesis, so here we present evidence from available empirical studies. &nbsp;Decreased dihydrotestosterone levels are most often noted as resulting from decreases in activities of enzymes in the Cyp11, Cyp17, p450, HSD3&beta;, and SR-B1 gene families.  Decreased steroidogenesis rates of androgen formation, associated with impaired steroidogenesis, have been linked to malformation of reproductive organs and decreased reproduction function through decreased dihydrotesterone levels (see Palermo et al. 2021 for review with focus on exposure to phthalates).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:12:06 +0000 2026"}